entry.title: [FilesBulkPinning] Expose kOkWithMoreResults drivefs result
entry.content:
When searching for items, it's possible to hit the end of the locally

available results but have some cloud results that are still potentially

available. This is only really required when the QuerySource is

`kLocalAndCloud` as it tries a local search first then defers to the

cloud.



Currently the logic is an empty page indicates the end of a query.

However when using `kLocalAndCloud` this logic is incorrect. To avoid

terminating the query at empty pages, provide another `FileError` called

`kOkWithMoreResults` to indicate the local results have been exhausted

and to try `GetNextPage` again to search the cloud. If the subsequent

search returns `kOk` with an empty page, this is the final result.



Bug: b:280240617, b:277018122

entry.title: Fix HasIsolatedStorage() for non-enabled extensions
entry.content:
HasIsolatedStorage() incorrectly returns false for extensions with

isolated storage that are not enabled, because it only checks the

enabled list.



This use case is relevant when an extension with isolated storage is

disabled. In this process, the extension is moved to the disabled list

of the ExtensionRegistry and then, among other actions, the extension

service worker is told to unregister. In order to obtain the service

worker context, HasIsolatedStorage() is used to determine the

StoragePartitionConfig of the extension. Because at this point the

extension is already moved to the disabled list, HasIsolatedStorage()

returns false, even though the extension has isolated storage and thus the incorrect ServiceWorkerContext is obtained (not the one in which

the extension actually has a service worker running). This leads to

the extensions's service worker not actually unregistering and still

running.



This issue is fixed by HasIsolatedStorage() checking the extensions in

both the enabled and disabled extension lists.



Bug: b:279763783

entry.title: Assign DelayBasedTimeSource::timer_ task runner when it is activated
entry.content:
The DelayBasedTimeSource may be constructed on a different thread

than the one it runs on. For example,

blink::WidgetBase::RequestNewLayerTreeFrameSink() runs on the blink

main thread, and if --disable-frame-rate-limit is specified it will

construct a BackToBackBeginFrameSource synchronously. This code path

isn't currently used, but we plan to use it when we start running

web_tests with threaded compositing by default.



DelayBasedTimeSource::SetActive, which must run on the same thread as

task_runner_, is the first point where timer_ needs to be correctly

set up, so call SetTaskRunner there.

entry.title: Don't bounds-check a history API navigation's offset in the renderer
entry.content:
When a history API navigation occurs (e.g., history.go(-2)), we

currently check whether the given offset is in-bounds before sending

the navigation to the browser. The spec and WPT expect an async step

to occur (i.e., going to the browser) so that we can take into

account any pending back/forward navigations in offset calculation.



However, when a history API navigation begins, we pause virtual time

if the navigation is in-bounds only. If we can't check that in

the renderer, we need of notifying the renderer that a history API

navigation was out of bounds so that we can unpause virtual time.

Add a case to the TraverseCancelled() message to unpause virtual

time and call it for out-of-bounds history API navigations.

(Note that TraverseCancelled() is currently only used for navigation

API traversals, but there's nothing stopping us from using the same

plumbing for this case).



This change gives us the correct behavior when history.back()

and history.forward() are called in rapid succession while at the

front of the back/forward list. The forward() should be calculated

from the pending entry for the back() navigation, resulting in

the two navigations cancelling each other out. The renderer doesn't

know what the pending offset is, so it thinks the forward() is trying

to go out-of-bounds and incorrectly rejects that navigation.

matches the last connected attach APN but not the last connected

and default APNs will be migrated with Enabled state.

network's apn_list, the last connected attach APN will be migrated with

Disabled state.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Preserve would be default match from legacy system.
entry.content:
This CL adds a feature variant that preserves the would-be default

match from the legacy scoring system. `SortAndCull` is called an extra

time before the ML model is invoked in order to determine what the

default match would've been.



This also has the side effect of limiting the matches shown after ML

scoring to only the matches that would've been shown in the legacy

system.



This CL also changes the `default_match_to_preserve` from a const

pointer to absl::optional. The pointer previously pointed to a match

that potentially went out of scope when leaving `UpdateResult()` and

was accessed inside the model callback. Additionally, when the results

are re-sorted, the match at that address can change. absl::optional

still allows us to pass an empty match but ensures that match stays

constant and still exists.

entry.title: [Windows] Rework Sandbox Process and Thread Intercepts.
entry.content:
This CL changes the process and thread intercepts in the Windows

sandbox. It first removes the IPC call for NtOpenProcess, as the

sandbox only supported opening the current process this is replaced

with a call to NtDuplicateObject. For NtOpenThread, NtDuplicateObject

will be used for opens for the current thread, only calling the IPC

if another thread ID is requested. Finally the NtOpenProcessToken and

NtOpenProcessTokenEx calls are merged and only the Ex IPC call is

maintained.
